         <abstract id="aspace_2b56b2d4907164ed51ac6d767b0a7c77">Correspondence, diaries, financial and legal papers, inventories, deeds, and accounts of members of the Pierpont family of North Haven, Connecticut. The principal figure is Daniel Pierpont, business man and town clerk of North Haven whose papers include an account book kept while building a house (1846), fourteen deeds for land in North Haven and a description of a churn invented by him. His diary (1824) contains an account of a murder trial in New Haven interrupted by the arrival of General Lafayette, and a description of a journey through southern New York state where he observed preparations for the reception of LaFayette. There is also an estate inventory for Hezekiah Pierpont (1792), financial papers of Rufus Pierpont and a resolution (Aug 1, 1855) of St. John's Church on his death.</abstract>
         <origination label="creator">
            <famname identifier="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2011001983"
                     source="lcsh">
               <part>Pierpont family</part>
            </famname>
         </origination>
    
